value.0: Possibly the remains of a sailor.
Skeletal remains from some poor sailor stick out from the kelp.
A sad pile of unidentified bones llies on the ground.
Hard to tell if this is a human or elven skeleton in the murky water.
Judging by the scraps of clothing wrapped around this skeleton, this place is a graveyard for more than just ships.

Whatever humanoid creature these remains are from, it certainly wasn't a human, elf, or dwarf. 

The skull seems to have been crushed by the sunken ship, so it's difficult to be sure what it was.

You assume this is the skeleton of a woman - mainly because of the dress the skeleton died wearing.

The big question: was she crew on one of the ships lying in this ship-graveyard, or merely an unlucky passenger, whose family awaits her eventual return, wondering whatever became of her. Chances are you'll never know.

You wonder if this is the remains of a pirate, or an honest sailor. 

Perhaps it doesn't matter - either way, they met their end at the bottom of the sea.
Judging by the crushed ribs, and the cannonball lodged in the chest of these remains, this sailor likely died in a sea battle on the surface. Perhaps a better death than drowning as his ship sank.
A rusted chest lies half-buried in the sand.
This partly-buried chest lies open and empty, lid creaking back and forth in the currents.
A rotted timber from one of the many wrecked ships.
A rather slimy plank of wood. You wonder how many unfortunate sailors stood upon that plank before taking their final swim to Davy Jones' Locker.
A rotted timber from one of the many wrecked ships.
A rotted mast, foremast most likely, from one of the many wrecked ships.
A rotted beam from one of the many wrecked ships.
This appears to have once been a ship's support beam, splintered by an unknown force, and half-rotten from the seawater.
A rotted timber from one of the many wrecked ships.
A rotted timber from one of the many wrecked ships.
A rockslide seems to have blocked the cave entrance. It looks dangerous and unstable.
The skull of some massive sea-beast sits half buried on the ocean floor.
Miscellaneous fish bones, heaped in a pile.
It looks like something broke this seashell open, possibly to get at the creature living within?
It's tough to tell in the murky water, but it looks like the husk of this starfish has...tooth marks? It's rather likely something ate this starfish, and discarded the remains.
From the look of it, someone has been discarding their supper-scraps here for some time. Many someones.
The bite marks imply this pile of fish bones is the remnants of many meals.
Mmm....seafood was the main (and only?) course, it seems.
It would seem someone...or something... has been collecting the skulls of the sailors from the shipwrecks. Hard to tell why - maybe as a warning, or perhaps as a territory marker.
This is the empty left eye socket of an ancient statue.
This is the empty right eye socket of an ancient statue.
This is the exit from sea cave: depths. One way.
this is where the ghost ship boss should spawn. the trigger should cover the entire "peninsula", so it cannot be bypassed
